title: For Sale:  German Navy Luger, with the very rare DuMond Carbine Barrel in 9mm
postcontent: 1920’s German Navy Luger, with the very rare DuMond Carbine Barrel, in 9mm. This Luger was turned in to the ultimate Match Target shooter sometime back in the 1930’s. The work was completed by the Legendary Target Barrel maker Mr. Du Mond of “Du Mond Manufacturing” (1930-1940). Du Mond gave this Luger a Custom heavy Luger Carbine barrel, and made the rear sight adjustable. If you ever wanted the ultimate Luger for Target shooting, this is it. Someone spent a lot of cash and time on this Navy Luger.This Navy Luger was worked on sometime in the 1930’s by Du Mond. You could only get this work done by sending your pistol to DuMond Manufacturing (1930-1940) From what I have learned, very few Luger pistols have these heavy custom Carbine barrel. There are only 6 known DuMond barrels for the 1906 Colt. I’ve never seen another Luger like this one.I found a few references to Du Mond barrels. 1) In “Pistols, a Modern Encyclopedia” by Henry Stebbins. His co-author Bert Shay describes ordering a Dumond barrel and sights for a 1903 Colt .32 ACP in 1945. Mr Dumond was deceased by the time that book came out in 1961, so information on the Gorenet will be lacking. Here is a video of a 1903 Colt w/ DuMond Barrel, found it interesting. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0LnTxQg-5fM2) Du Mond barrels were custom order only and I believe JACK O'CONNOR spoke of having a Springfield barreled with one. Elmer Keith mentioned liking them. Dumond died in 1943 or 1944 and the business was sold to someone, but they couldn't make a go of it. I have heard he made the majority of his barrels for rifles.This is no ordinary pistol. This Luger was customized by one of the best (legendary) Custom Target Makers of his time, Mr. Du Mond. This 1920 Luger was almost new when DuMond (1930’s) made this a target pistol.Could only upload 3 photo's, can send more.Will consider trades of equal value + -** I believe this has Sold, will remove when transaction has completed **

title: For Sale:  Ithaca .22 Model M-49
location: St. Paul, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: Ithaca Model M-49 .22 caliber rifle for sale.  These were manufactured from 1961 to 1978-79 and no records were kept on the serial #'s, so the exact age is unknown.  My Dad bought this some time after he got back from Vietnam and was killed in a car accident when I was 10.  It was passed on to my older brother and a few years later he gave it to me when I was 12 years old (1986) and I went through firearm safety training.  It has been well used and loved, but I haven't fired it in years and have no kids to pass it onto.  It has some wear and tear on the bluing and wood, but is in pretty good shape overall.  It's time to clear a spot in the gun safe and hopefully find it a new home where someone else's son or daughter will love it as much as I did.  This is a lever action, single shot rifle that will fire .22 shorts and .22 lr (no mags).  The tube gives it the appearance of storage, but you drop the lever, load the round in the chamber, pull the lever back up, and pull back the hammer in order to fire it.  Dropping the lever again will eject the shell casing.  It seems tedious, but as a kid it taught me to shoot carefully and accurately with only that one round when I'd take it out shooting.  It's hard to put a value on this thing, the gun boards are all over the place.  I'm putting a price tag of $200 on it, but will consider reasonable offers.  I own my own residential HVAC company and I travel all over the cities for work, so meeting up around the metro is not an issue for me if given some advance notice.  If interested, include a # I can reach you at and I will contact you quickly.  I am extremely busy this time of year and travel alot, so I'd prefer to text or talk on the phone.  It's just so much faster.  Thanks for understanding!
